    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>15 Marine Parade | Eastbourne</placeName>
                    <date>Monday 23<hi rend="superscript">d</hi></date>
                    <seg type="supplemental"><hi rend="italic">To M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> </hi> <hi rend="italic">Norman </hi></seg>
                    <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>Please copy this letter<ref target="#foot.f2"/> <hi rend="underline">as soon as you can</hi> on folio page, writing on both sides &amp; send it me by Post, paying postage &amp; charging it to me.—<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p>
<p>Yours faithfully | C. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
            
            
            
            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">In 1860, 23 September was actually a Sunday. CD made the same error about the date in the following letter, but then corrected it.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">CD refers to the draft of a letter to <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_2161.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">William Henry Harvey</ref> (see letter to W. H. Harvey, [20–4 September]). The letter to Norman was written on the verso of the first sheet of the draft.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">A payment to Norman for copying, which may have included this transaction, is recorded in CD’s Account book (Down House MS) on 26 April 1861.</note>
        </div>        
            
